The game is a real challenge, giving you building blocks to creat solutions. Some are tightly constrained puzzles, some are wide open problems to solve however you choose. This will give you a real brain workout. If the dev makes more of these, sign me up!
Definitely not a disappointing, but a very refeshing sequel! Is there anyway to know the optimal score of a level?
Quite clever. Easy to pick up and understand, but challenging to complete. For 5 stars I am missing a way to skip puzzles.
This is brilliant (bit different than v1). Please keep making great games!

The mechanics seem alright but the tutorial is extremely slow and restrictive. Even just allowing fast forward to be used and not repeating the same puzzle would make it much more tolerable. I honestly don't want to deal with the tutorials when Zachtronic games don't have this issue.

Loved the first game and love this one even more. This isn't just a rehash of the same stuff. It's a different and expanded experience while retaining the essence of the first game. For one thing it's hexagonal instead of on a grid. The levels have different boundaries. Multiple source and destination points. Objects must be delivered properly oriented. Many more levels. Different machines. I highly recommend both games. Best few bucks I've ever spent. Similar to zachtronics games.
A great puzzle game, much like the Zachtronic series on PC.

Adds a third axis to an already brilliant concept. Just as frustrating and rewarding as the first game, which I recommend playing first. It's very hard to shake the feeling that you just need to change two numbers for your sequence to work, even when you're miles away from the solution. Here's a tip for when you get stuck: chuck your spaghetti in the bin, start over and try to think ahead this time.
UI needs a small tweak. For the level selection screen, can you open the screen with the latest unsolved level? I've to scroll many pages to reach it everytime I start the game now. Very annoying.

This is a great little puzzle game, similar in nature to Zachtronic games such as Spacechem. The levels are designed nicely, with the potential for lots of clever solutions. In contrast to Zachtronic games, the puzzles here are mostly a lot less open ended (for the earlier levels in particular, you are trying to figure out the 'trick' that will make a solution possible.) The levels ramp up nicely in difficulty, and are worth revisiting to optimise later on as you gain an appreciation for how the gadgets work together. I think that people who aren't good at logical puzzle games could find this game frustrating, but to everybody else this is easy to recommend. If it was several times the price, it would still be easily worth the money.

Amazing puzzle game. It's constantly challenging you to come up with new ways of approaching puzzles. The levels feel designed, not generated, and you actually feel like you've accomplished something when you finally solve it unlike stuff like Candy Crush.
Love it
One of the best hardcore puzzle game available! Great puzzle design and rewardingly deep game mechanics.
Well implemented, good design, cool concept, challenging puzzles.
In general a good game, but keeps asking for more unneeded Google profile data after denial on later startups. I paid, don't ask for anything more than you need.
loved the game but i don't understand what exactly the A and B option and copy button do, what's the point? am i missing something?
replyContent: Almost 80% of the levels have a second solution. You can try to find them. Starting with level 47 you will be able to save your solutions in special slots A and B.

content: The game is excellent but, ultimately, its replayability is limited by the hard level cap and lack of secondary objectives (reduce number of cycles, resource waste, symbols used, etc.). Player-made challenge maps and a level editor would be cool.

Loved the original. This is a worthy sequel. Really smart. Would go 5 stars, but some basic features are missing:  No way to skip a puzzle you're stuck on. Gives "points" for solving with fewer pieces... but those are never used - in original game you could buy single move hints with them. It should remember where i left off when i close the app, instead of making you go through the whole list to get back to the next level. One other real concern is how much battery this app consumes - I've seen it drain 20% of my battery life in 15-20 minutes, which is a lot for a game that doesn't have a bunch of fancy 3-D rendering to do.  It makes me wonder what is really going on under the hood.
A bit like The Human Recource Machine. Not as complex but even more challenging! Highly recommended.

i never rate games. never. but i felt compelled to say that this game is exceptional. i own it on both iOS and Android. if you like a challenging puzzle game and you're a coder, get this. you wont be sorry.

People who haven't played the original are going to find this tough, particularly if their background isn't in some kind of mechanical/electrical/computer engineering  Great game, though.
